WEBVTT

NOTE
AI 2027 Report: Reality Check — Kokoro TTS Version
Re-render of the original episode for voice quality A/B comparison.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Introduction & Report Overview. The AI 2027 report, written by Daniel Kokotajlo and collaborators, attempted to forecast AI development through 2027. Now that we're deep into 2026, how well did it hold up?

00:01:30.000 --> 00:03:15.000
The Core Thesis. The report predicted rapid capability gains, agent proliferation, and a concentration of AI power in a handful of US labs — with AGI potentially arriving by late 2027.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:05:00.000
The Authors' Own Revision. The authors themselves revised their timeline — pushing the AGI estimate from 2027 to approximately 2030. That's a three-year slip on their own forecast, which tells you something.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:07:30.000
What They Got Right. Agent development has followed their trajectory almost exactly. Coding AI emerged as the leading indicator. Government has remained behind the curve. Safety risks becoming visible — all validated.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Mixed Results. The general direction of capability improvement is correct. But the speed and the competitive dynamics were off. The assumption that a small number of well-resourced US labs would dominate didn't survive contact with DeepSeek.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Where They Missed. The smooth scaling thesis has been challenged. China prediction was wrong — private enterprise, not state nationalization. The compute-concentration thesis didn't hold.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:11:30.000
The DeepSeek Surprise. An under-resourced Chinese startup training frontier models for approximately six million dollars was not in anyone's scenario planning. That single data point invalidated a core assumption about the capital requirements for frontier AI.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:37:00.000
Overall Grade & Opinion. B-minus for direction, D for timing. The what is right even if the when is wrong. The report remains valuable as a framework for thinking about AI trajectories — even though the specific timeline has been revised by its own authors.

